    id: 'dewey',
    imageUrl: '/images/philosophers/dewey.svg',
    name: 'John Dewey',
    era: '1859-1952',
    bio: `John Dewey was the central American philosopher of the twentieth century's first half, the one thinker in the pragmatist tradition whose work ranges with equal seriousness across epistemology, ethics, political theory, education, aesthetics, and what would now be called social technology. Born in Burlington, Vermont, in 1859 to a grocer's family, educated at the University of Vermont and then at Johns Hopkins in the first American graduate program in philosophy, and shaped by Hegel, William James, and Charles Sanders Peirce, he spent a long career — eighty-five active years as a philosopher, more than forty books, and thousands of essays — arguing that inquiry is not a private cognitive event but a social practice by which communities learn to deal with genuinely difficult situations. He taught at Michigan, Chicago, and finally Columbia; he signed the founding charter of the NAACP in 1909; he helped establish the American Association of University Professors; he was the most publicly engaged American philosopher of his generation and perhaps of the entire twentieth century.

The most distinctive feature of his thought is the insistence that knowledge and action are continuous — that knowing and doing are two phases of the same process — and that any ethics which treats them as separable has already mistaken what ethics is. For Dewey, a belief is not an internal state but a disposition to act; a value is not a private preference but a pattern of engagement with the world; an inquiry is not a solo contemplation but a collaborative response to what he called a "problematic situation," a context in which prior habits no longer produce the outcomes the community had come to expect. The implication for ethics is radical. We do not first work out what is good and then apply it to cases; we encounter situations that break our existing practices, we work together to restore coherence, and the values that emerge from that collaborative work are the only values the term has ever actually named.

His technology ethics emerge from that commitment. Dewey never wrote a treatise called "The Ethics of Technology," but the books that most directly bear on it — Democracy and Education (1916), The Public and Its Problems (1927), Liberalism and Social Action (1935), Experience and Nature (1925) — all treat the specific tools by which a society organizes its inquiry as moral and political artifacts. A school is a technology. A newspaper is a technology. A voting system is a technology. A corporate form is a technology. Each one structures what inquiries a community can sustain, who can participate, what can be named as a problem, and what solutions are pre-approved as respectable. The moral question in each case is what capacities the tool cultivates in the people operating it, and whether those capacities are the ones a democracy requires.

The Public and Its Problems is the central text for contemporary tech-ethics readers. Writing in 1927, Dewey argued that modern communications and industrial technologies had created a world in which the publics that were affected by decisions could no longer identify themselves. When a factory in one city poisons a river that flows through three others, the affected public is the residents of four cities — but none of those cities has the institutional machinery to notice the shared situation as a shared situation, and so the collective actor who would be needed to address it never forms. Dewey called this "the eclipse of the public," and his diagnosis has aged into alarming relevance. The populations affected by algorithmic hiring, by platform content moderation, by cross-border surveillance, by supply-chain labor conditions, by climate emissions — these are Dewey's eclipsed publics, and a democracy whose publics cannot form is a democracy only in name. This is why "public" is the right word for public-interest technology rather than a substitute for it.

Dewey's deepest influence has been on education, because schools were the point where he thought the moral question was most tractable. His Laboratory School at the University of Chicago, founded in 1896, was an operational argument that learning is a social activity organized around genuine problems rather than a private transfer of information, and that a democracy that does not cultivate the capacities of inquiry in its children will not sustain itself when those children become citizens. The argument cut against both traditional didactic schooling (which treated the child as an empty vessel) and the narrower "child-centered" progressivism that sometimes claimed him (which treated any structure as coercion). Dewey's position was more interesting than either: learning happens when a student encounters a real problem she cares about and works with others toward its resolution, and the teacher's job is to design the conditions under which such encounters reliably occur. The parallels to contemporary debates about AI in education are obvious and mostly unflattering to both sides of that debate.

The pragmatist framework pairs unusually productively with contemporary tech-ethics work. Where Kantian ethics asks whether a maxim can be universalized, pragmatist ethics asks whether a practice can sustain the inquiry community that would have to evaluate it — a subtly different question that is harder to evade. Where utilitarian ethics optimizes over a specified welfare measure, pragmatist ethics treats the specification itself as a political act and asks whose interests the measurement embeds. Where virtue ethics locates moral agency in the cultivated individual, pragmatist ethics distributes it across the institutions that form such individuals, and locates responsibility for design defects in those institutions rather than in the individual "bad actor" narrative that most tech crises end up producing. A Deweyan reading of the Cambridge Analytica scandal, for instance, would focus less on the individual malfeasance of the parties involved than on the absence of institutional machinery that could have allowed the affected publics to identify themselves and respond — and on the design choices that made such machinery impossible.

Dewey's relationship to the subsequent continental tradition is closer than the stereotyped "analytic vs. continental" split suggests. Jürgen Habermas has acknowledged Dewey as a direct predecessor for discourse ethics; the public-sphere concept Habermas develops is in many ways a neo-Deweyan reconstruction. Martha Nussbaum has cited Dewey extensively in her work on capabilities. Richard Rorty read him as the single most important American philosopher and tried to bring him back into conversation with continental philosophy. Alain Locke, the Harvard-educated founder of the Harlem Renaissance's philosophical wing and the first African American Rhodes Scholar, was Dewey's student and colleague and extended the pragmatist framework into race and cultural pluralism in ways Dewey himself did not always manage.

For the contemporary technology-ethics reader, Dewey supplies what other ethical traditions often lack: a way of treating the social mechanisms by which a community decides what to do about a new tool as themselves part of the ethical object. A Kantian or utilitarian analysis can evaluate a specific technology policy; a Deweyan analysis asks what inquiry capacities the policy process itself requires and cultivates. In a moment when the question of how democracies absorb algorithmic, informational, and biotechnological change is unresolved, Dewey's insistence that the practice of inquiry is itself a moral infrastructure has become, again, one of the most useful frames available. The engineers, regulators, and civic technologists working on platform governance, on AI oversight, on algorithmic accountability — they are, whether or not they know it, working on Dewey's eclipsed-public problem, and the depth of his hundred-year-old diagnosis is still ahead of most of the proposed solutions.`,
