    id: 'williams',
    imageUrl: '/images/philosophers/williams.svg',
    name: 'Bernard Williams',
    era: '1929-2003',
    bio: `Bernard Arthur Owen Williams was a British philosopher trained at Balliol College, Oxford, a professor successively at Bedford College, Cambridge, Berkeley, and Oxford again, and — by the judgment of colleagues across many disagreements — one of the most incisive moral philosophers of the second half of the twentieth century. Born in 1929, he served briefly in the RAF, married and later divorced the Labour politician Shirley Williams, chaired three major British Royal Commissions (on gambling, on obscenity and film censorship, and on drugs), and wrote the introduction to the 1979 edition of Descartes that changed how a generation read the Meditations. What he was best at was refusing the shapes that moral philosophy was handed down to him. He read Kant and utilitarianism and the analytic tradition with care and found, in each, assumptions about the moral life that, when examined, looked less like neutral frames than like specific pictures of what a person is — pictures that could not carry the weight the theories placed on them.

His most durable contribution is the critique of impartialism developed in essays like "A Critique of Utilitarianism" (1973) and "Persons, Character, and Morality" (1976). The picture of moral agency inherited from Kant and from the utilitarians imagines the agent as a detached rational chooser who weighs all persons' interests equally. Williams's argument was that such an agent would not be a person at all — that the particular ground projects, loves, commitments, and identifications that make an individual's life distinctively theirs cannot be abstracted from without destroying the agent whose agency the theory is trying to evaluate. To demand of a person that they be equally available to all claims from all parties is to demand that they have no integrity at the cost of having any interior at all. The Jim-and-the-Indians case Williams constructed in his Utilitarianism: For and Against exchange with J. J. C. Smart is the clearest working-out: a utilitarian calculus can produce the verdict that Jim should shoot one person to prevent twenty others from being shot, and the calculus is in some technical sense correct, but the person who does shoot would have to be a person for whom no particular act of taking a life was a personal catastrophe. That person, Williams observed, would not be Jim.

The associated concepts — agent-regret, moral luck, integrity, thick and thin ethical concepts, internal and external reasons — all press in the same direction. Agent-regret names the specific emotion a person feels when their action produces harm without their fault, which Williams argued is evidence that even "blameless" choice carries a weight consequentialist analysis cannot capture. Moral luck names the fact that whether we count as good or bad people depends substantially on what actually happens — the same choices, under different outcomes, would produce different ethical evaluations — which is deeply uncomfortable but, Williams argued, undeniable in ordinary practice. Thick ethical concepts (cruelty, cowardice, generosity, dishonesty) carry descriptive and evaluative content that cannot be cleanly separated; thin ones (right, good, ought) can be separated but at the cost of losing most of what makes them useful.

Ethics and the Limits of Philosophy (1985) is Williams's most sustained book-length argument and the one most relevant to contemporary tech-ethics work. He argued that the ancient Greek question "how should one live?" is more fruitful than the modern question "what am I morally required to do?" precisely because it admits the full range of what matters in a human life rather than pre-filtering to what a universal theory can handle. The book ends with a startling claim: philosophy can, at best, help us hold onto the ethical knowledge we already have. It cannot provide it from the outside. The implication for AI-ethics frameworks, for corporate codes of ethics, for any project that tries to "derive" morality from first principles, is bracing and unflattering.

Williams's engagement with moral luck is particularly useful for technology ethics. Consider an engineer who ships a feature that, due to an unforeseeable downstream interaction with another team's code, produces harm. Standard ethical frameworks struggle to answer whether the engineer is blameworthy; Williams would insist that this difficulty is not a bug in ethical reasoning but a load-bearing feature of how responsibility actually works. The engineer bears something — not pure blame, not pure exoneration, but a specific moral residue Williams called agent-regret — and the institutional response has to engage with that residue rather than pretend it can be dispatched by a verdict. Contemporary incident-response culture in software engineering (blameless postmortems, psychological safety, root-cause analysis) is doing Williamsian ethics in practice, and the places where it goes wrong are the places where it tries to flatten the residue out of existence.

The critique of the "one thought too many" problem, developed in "Persons, Character, and Morality," is Williams's most-quoted argument. If a person, faced with the choice of saving their drowning spouse or a drowning stranger, pauses to check whether saving their spouse is morally justifiable, they have already demonstrated a defect in the kind of person they are. The justification was supposed to be: it's my spouse. To require a further layer of impartial reasoning is to demand a kind of interior life that would be, Williams argued, actually worse than the one the theory was trying to improve. The argument cuts against the universalization tests that dominate AI-ethics frameworks, and it pairs with the care-ethics critique of impartialism Noddings and Gilligan developed independently around the same time.

For technology ethics, Williams supplies the most rigorous available critique of the assumption that moral questions about technology can be resolved by application of a principle. When a utilitarian cost-benefit analysis produces a verdict that conflicts with a person's sense of what they can live with having done, Williams insists that the sense is data rather than noise. When a Kantian universalization test produces an answer that could only be reached by a person stripped of the commitments that constitute them, the test is suspect. When an AI-safety framework proposes that "aligned AI" is AI whose behavior is predictable from a specified objective function, Williams's response is that the specification itself is a theoretical artifact and that the fluency of the argument is not evidence of its grip on reality.

His work underpins a generation of moral philosophers who treat lived moral experience as genuine evidence, and for anyone trying to think clearly about what we owe in the face of algorithmic decision-making, automation of moral labor, or the reorganization of everyday agency, the resistance he developed to theory-driven flattening is essential equipment. Williams died in 2003. Contemporary moral philosophy is still working out the implications of the challenges he left.`,
